President Obama and Prime Minister Abe of Japan had a phone call to discuss their concerns about the use of chemical weapons in Syria. They both agreed that this is a serious violation of international norms and cannot be tolerated. They also pledged to consult closely on possible responses by the international community. The two leaders also emphasized the importance of the U.S.-Japan alliance for the peace and stability of the Asia-Pacific region. They expressed their commitment to enhancing security cooperation on regional and global challenges and continuing the implementation of their shared plan for U.S. force posture realignment in Japan. President Obama also highlighted the importance of concluding the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) negotiations this fall and both leaders agreed to consult closely on the way forward.